SUBJ: Site Plan/Traffic Advisory Committee Meeting – Tuesday, June 10, 2014
There will be a meeting of the Site Plan/Traffic Advisory Committee on Tuesday, June
10, 2014 at 1:00 P.M. in the Minnesota Valley Conference Room. The following items
will be reviewed at the meeting.
1. Conditional Use Permit – Allow for a Grouped Housing Project in the R-4,
Multiple-Family Dwelling District – Devonshire Subdivision –Devonshire II
2. Preliminary and Final Plat – Maple View Townhomes – Umashankar
Subramanian– Rezoning from PI, Planned Industrial and M-2, Heavy Industrial to
R-2, One and Two-Family Dwelling District – Conditional Use Permit to Allow
for Grouped Housing Project – Outlot G, Sibley Parkway
3. Certificate of Design Compliance – Office Building to be Located in the
Downtown Gateway Overlay District – Tailwind Group – 115 W. Cherry Street
4. Conditional Use Permit – Allow for a Restaurant in the B-1, Community Business
District – Heidi Wyn – 529 N. Riverfront Drive
5. Variance – Reduce Front Yard Setback from 30 Feet to 6 Feet for Purpose of
Constructing a Detached Garage – John Mayberry – 10 North Hill Court
6. Site Plan – Agstar Parking Lot Expansion – 1921 Premier Drive
7. Site Plan – Hardee’s Restaurant – Vicinity of West Lind Court and North River
8. Site Plan – USPS Carrier Relocation – Summit Avenue
1. South Front Street Sidewalk Café Design Guidelines
2. License to Encroach – Mock’s Landscaping, 800 N. Riverfront Drive
5. No Parking Signs, E. Main Street East of Victory Drive
6. Discussion – Stop Sign on Ramsey Street
7. Discussion – Limit Access at Ramsey and Highland/Warren Street
8. Discussion – Possible Traffic Calming near Lincoln Community Center
COG Report for May will be added to packet and sent separately to Committee when
If you have any questions regarding the items, please contact me at extension 571.

Update on Hickory Street/Riverfront Drive Pedestrian Crossings
Mr. Vogel advised that the City Manager is requesting options for installation of a
flasher/warning sign, with pedestrian trigger button, for this intersection. Engineering staff noted
the cost is approximately $1,800 per sign, and approximately $7,500 total for the crossing
project. Mr. Vogel advised that a report should be forward from the City Engineer to City
Mr. Bode provided an overview of the request, noting concern with location of the power pole
and how unloading of trucks across the street will be accommodated, but not other issues from
his standpoint. The proposed curbcut would be 20’ wide.
Discussion amongst the Committee noted that all gravel areas must be either hardsurfaced or
returned to being grass. As the property owner of part of the property, Tailwind Group must be a
Once Tailwind Group application signature is received, the application is to be forwarded to

Request for Private Parking on Public Street – Hubbell Avenue
Mr. Johnson gave an overview of the request, noting it is a significant improvement for parking
The Committee recommended approval. This item is to be forwarded to the Multi-Modal
Review of Proposed Front Street Renderings
Mr. Wasmund noted a comment brought up by Mr. Bengston, who was unable to attend the
meeting, regarding the depicted bollards. Staff noted that the bollards would be of a breakaway
design and that they would coordinate with Department of Public Safety – Fire on the final
designs. Consideration may be given to revising bollard spacing to approximately 12’.
Engineering staff provided an overview of other elements, included angled parking on both sides
of the 600 block of S. Front Street, with 20 foot drive lands, and parallel parking on both sides of
It was also noted that every light pole will have the capability of accepting a camera mount, and
that camera visibility is factored in with plans for plantings and tree trimming.
Staff also noted that there have been discussions with Walgreens regarding possible removal of
one curbcut access on South Front in order to allow for additional on-street parking.
Proposed Reverse Angled Parking – Malin Street
Mr. Bode noted that this is the Children’s House location at MSU, and that he had been
contacted today with a request to remove this idea and instead request 90 degree parking, which
he noted was not approved in other locations.
Discussion amongst the Committee advised that there appears to be enough lot area for them to
comply with the standards, same as was done for other similar requests. There was also noted
concern that this area may be utilized for permit parking, as drop-off/pick-up often occurs on the
eastern side of the property. It was also noted that there is adequate room for additional of a
small parking lot area as well.
The Committee advised that the proposal would have to comply with the same requirements as
were used for St. Mark’s and St. Joseph’s, and that it would require an agreement for private use
It was also recommended that the request be brought to the Highland Park Neighborhood
Association by MSU officials for discussion prior to re-submittal.
Mr. Bode gave an overview of the proposed update, noting that this plan also has Safe Routes to
School (SRS) integrated. Areas in green are proposed connections.
Committee discussion advised that the plan should also distinctly note areas proposed in the
1996 plan that haven’t yet been completed.
The Committee selected several representatives from different departments to review the map
and provide comment. Selected members are Landon Bode, Joe Grabianowski, Mark Konz, and
Street Striping Changes – Main Street & Pohl Road
Mr. Bode first provided options for Main Street, including possible changes from 2 lane to 3 lane
sections, noting that it fits within the existing configuration until Agency Road. No parking
would be allowed on the north side, but it would be allowed on the south side of the street. The
option for inclusion of bike lanes was also discussed.
Mr. Johnson advised that there should be a public meeting in the area to present options and
gather comments. Resurrection Lutheran Church, 1735 E. Main Street, was noted as a possible
The recommendation was for Engineering staff to hold a public meeting to gather input before
Mr. Bode presented concepts for Pohl Road, noting that it is too narrow for a bike lane but they
are trying to make it bike-friendly. He presented three options for the area.
The Committee recommended also holding a meeting with neighborhood residents for input, and
also recommended that Engineering staff contact bike/walk advocates for their input. It was
noted that hopefully at least a “share the road” design could be implemented, with possible
inclusion of a bike lane where space is available.
The Committee discussed the proposed policy. It was noted that banners would only be allowed
on poles that are set up for their use, and that an event schedule is utilized. The Committee noted
that use of the word “constitutions” should be clarified.
The Committee recommended approval of the policy. The item should be forwarded to the
Multi-Modal Committee for review, and then to the City Manager.
Mr. Johnson gave an overview of the policy to the Committee, noting that its creation and use is
part of a federal requirement. He advised that the policy has been modeled in-part on a model
policy issued by the League of Minnesota Cities. When new signs are installed, they must have
a schedule for maintenance, and the policy also establishes maintenance priorities.
It was noted that testing of existing signs indicated approximately 1,700 are in the “fail”
category, and represent a cost of nearly $200,000 to replace and install.
The Committee recommended approval of the policy. The item should be forwarded to the
Multi-Modal Committee for review, and then to the City Manager.
Traffic Control – Pohl Road/Timberwolf Drive Intersection
Mr. Vogel advised that the Committee has been asked to work on reviewing this area again, as it
was brought up at a Planning Commission meeting by neighbors from the area that were in
attendance. The Planning Commission adopted a recommendation that the intersection be a
Yield Sign on N. Augusta Drive
The Committee was unable to review or make recommendation on this item due to time
constraints. The item will be circulated by Engineering for comment and review.

3.03 Plants shall be well branched and bushy with good color, plant size
should be in proportion to the pot as described by the American Standard for

with the minimum standards of ANSI z60 - the American Standard for
Nursery Stock. Trees may not have been topped (upright branches at top of
may not be cut or pruned).
3.04 Plants shall exceed the minimum size at planting requirements noted

will be allowed for use of larger container plants. Measurements shall be
made with the plant in a natural, unsupported position.
3.05 Plants specified as "gallon," "container," or "box" on the plans shall
conform to the ANSI z60, American Standard for Nursery Stock requirements

3.06 Tree calipers shall be measured 6 inches above the rootball per ANSI
z60, American Standard for Nursery Stock. Tree heights shall be measured
from top of rootball to top of highest branch.
3.07 Trees shall be planted 4'0" or more from hardscapes, such as
sidewalks, foundations, curbs, patios, etc. when possible.
3.08 Trees shall not be planted within 4'0" of buried utility lines, relocate
trees slightly, if not possible notify landscape architect.

edges, import top soil if necessary to comply with this requirement.
3.11 All sod turf shall be rolled with a weighted roller after installation.
